#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:-1
msgid ""
"An overview of the Autotools build system in Spack for packages that use GNU "
"Autotools."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:13
msgid "Autotools"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:15
msgid ""
"Autotools is a GNU build system that provides a build-script generator. By "
"running the platform-independent ``./configure`` script that comes with the "
"package, you can generate a platform-dependent Makefile."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:19
msgid "Phases"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:21
msgid ""
"The ``AutotoolsBuilder`` and ``AutotoolsPackage`` base classes come with the "
"following phases:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:23
msgid "``autoreconf`` - generate the configure script"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:24
msgid "``configure`` - generate the Makefiles"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:25
msgid "``build`` - build the package"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:26
msgid "``install`` - install the package"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:28
msgid ""
"Most of the time, the ``autoreconf`` phase will do nothing, but if the "
"package is missing a ``configure`` script, ``autoreconf`` will generate one "
"for you."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:30
msgid "The other phases run:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:32
msgid ""
"$ ./configure --prefix=/path/to/installation/prefix\n"
"$ make\n"
"$ make check  # optional\n"
"$ make install\n"
"$ make installcheck  # optional"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:41
msgid ""
"Of course, you may need to add a few arguments to the ``./configure`` line."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:44
msgid "Important files"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:46
msgid ""
"The most important file for an Autotools-based package is the ``configure`` "
"script. This script is automatically generated by Autotools and generates "
"the appropriate Makefile when run."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:51
msgid "Watch out for fake Autotools packages!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:53
msgid ""
"Autotools is a very popular build system, and many people are used to the "
"classic steps to install a package:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:55
msgid ""
"$ ./configure\n"
"$ make\n"
"$ make install"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:62
msgid ""
"For this reason, some developers will write their own ``configure`` scripts "
"that have nothing to do with Autotools. These packages may not accept the "
"same flags as other Autotools packages, so it is better to use the "
"``Package`` base class and create a :ref:`custom build system "
"<custompackage>`. You can tell if a package uses Autotools by running ``./"
"configure --help`` and comparing the output to other known Autotools "
"packages. You should also look for files like:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:67
msgid "``configure.ac``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:68
msgid "``configure.in``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:69
msgid "``Makefile.am``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:71
msgid "Packages that don't use Autotools aren't likely to have these files."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:74
msgid "Build system dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:76
msgid ""
"Whether or not your package requires Autotools to install depends on how the "
"source code is distributed. Most of the time, when developers distribute "
"tarballs, they will already contain the ``configure`` script necessary for "
"installation. If this is the case, your package does not require any "
"Autotools dependencies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:80
msgid ""
"However, a basic rule of version control systems is to never commit code "
"that can be generated. The source code repository itself likely does not "
"have a ``configure`` script. Developers typically write (or auto-generate) a "
"``configure.ac`` script that contains configuration preferences and a "
"``Makefile.am`` script that contains build instructions. Then, ``autoconf`` "
"is used to convert ``configure.ac`` into ``configure``, while ``automake`` "
"is used to convert ``Makefile.am`` into ``Makefile.in``. ``Makefile.in`` is "
"used by ``configure`` to generate a platform-dependent ``Makefile`` for you. "
"The following diagram provides a high-level overview of the process:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:90
msgid ""
"`GNU autoconf and automake process for generating makefiles <https://commons."
"wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Autoconf-automake-process.svg>`_ by `Jdthood` under "
"`CC BY-SA 3.0 <https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/deed.en>`_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:93
msgid ""
"If a ``configure`` script is not present in your tarball, you will need to "
"generate one yourself. Luckily, Spack already has an ``autoreconf`` phase to "
"do most of the work for you. By default, the ``autoreconf`` phase runs:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:97
msgid ""
"$ autoreconf --install --verbose --force -I <aclocal-prefix>/share/aclocal"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:101
msgid ""
"In case you need to add more arguments, override ``autoreconf_extra_args`` "
"in your ``package.py`` on class scope like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:103
msgid "autoreconf_extra_args = [\"-Im4\"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:107
msgid ""
"All you need to do is add a few Autotools dependencies to the package. Most "
"stable releases will come with a ``configure`` script, but if you check out "
"a commit from the ``master`` branch, you would want to add:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:110
msgid ""
"depends_on(\"autoconf\", type=\"build\", when=\"@master\")\n"
"depends_on(\"automake\", type=\"build\", when=\"@master\")\n"
"depends_on(\"libtool\", type=\"build\", when=\"@master\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:116
msgid ""
"It is typically redundant to list the ``m4`` macro processor package as a "
"dependency, since ``autoconf`` already depends on it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:119
msgid "Using a custom autoreconf phase"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:121
msgid ""
"In some cases, it might be needed to replace the default implementation of "
"the autoreconf phase with one running a script interpreter. In this example, "
"the ``bash`` shell is used to run the ``autogen.sh`` script."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:124
msgid ""
"def autoreconf(self, spec, prefix):\n"
"    which(\"bash\")(\"autogen.sh\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:129
msgid ""
"If the ``package.py`` has build instructions in a separate :ref:`builder "
"class <multiple_build_systems>`, the signature for a phase changes slightly:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:131
msgid ""
"class AutotoolsBuilder(AutotoolsBuilder):\n"
"    def autoreconf(self, pkg, spec, prefix):\n"
"        which(\"bash\")(\"autogen.sh\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:138
msgid "patching configure or Makefile.in files"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:140
msgid ""
"In some cases, developers might need to distribute a patch that modifies one "
"of the files used to generate ``configure`` or ``Makefile.in``. In this "
"case, these scripts will need to be regenerated. It is preferable to "
"regenerate these manually using the patch, and then create a new patch that "
"directly modifies ``configure``. That way, Spack can use the secondary patch "
"and additional build system dependencies aren't necessary."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:146
msgid "Old Autotools helper scripts"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:148
msgid ""
"Autotools based tarballs come with helper scripts such as ``config.sub`` and "
"``config.guess``. It is the responsibility of the developers to keep these "
"files up to date so that they run on every platform, but for very old "
"software releases this is impossible. In these cases Spack can help to "
"replace these files with newer ones, without having to add the heavy "
"dependency on ``automake``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:152
msgid ""
"Automatic helper script replacement is currently enabled by default on "
"``ppc64le`` and ``aarch64``, as these are the known cases where old scripts "
"fail. On these targets, ``AutotoolsPackage`` adds a build dependency on "
"``gnuconfig``, which is a very lightweight package with newer versions of "
"the helper files. Spack then tries to run all the helper scripts it can find "
"in the release, and replaces them on failure with the helper scripts from "
"``gnuconfig``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:156
msgid "To opt out of this feature, use the following setting:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:158
msgid "patch_config_files = False"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:162
msgid ""
"To enable it conditionally on different architectures, define a property and "
"make the package depend on ``gnuconfig`` as a build dependency:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:164
msgid ""
"depends_on(\"gnuconfig\", when=\"@1.0:\")\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@property\n"
"def patch_config_files(self):\n"
"    return self.spec.satisfies(\"@1.0:\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:175
msgid ""
"On some exotic architectures it is necessary to use system provided ``config."
"sub`` and ``config.guess`` files. In this case, the most transparent "
"solution is to mark the ``gnuconfig`` package as external and non-buildable, "
"with a prefix set to the directory containing the files:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:178
msgid ""
"gnuconfig:\n"
"  buildable: false\n"
"  externals:\n"
"  - spec: gnuconfig@master\n"
"    prefix: /usr/share/configure_files/"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:188
msgid "force_autoreconf"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:190
msgid ""
"If for whatever reason you really want to add the original patch and tell "
"Spack to regenerate ``configure``, you can do so using the following setting:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:192
msgid "force_autoreconf = True"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:196
msgid ""
"This line tells Spack to wipe away the existing ``configure`` script and "
"generate a new one. If you only need to do this for a single version, this "
"can be done like so:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:199
msgid ""
"@property\n"
"def force_autoreconf(self):\n"
"    return self.version == Version(\"1.2.3\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:206
msgid "Finding configure flags"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:208
msgid ""
"Once you have a ``configure`` script present, the next step is to determine "
"what option flags are available. These flags can be found by running:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:211
msgid "$ ./configure --help"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:215
msgid ""
"``configure`` will display a list of valid flags separated into some or all "
"of the following sections:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:217
msgid "Configuration"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:218
msgid "Installation directories"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:219
msgid "Fine tuning of the installation directories"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:220
msgid "Program names"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:221
msgid "X features"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:222
msgid "System types"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:223
msgid "**Optional Features**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:224
msgid "**Optional Packages**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:225
msgid "**Some influential environment variables**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:227
msgid ""
"For the most part, you can ignore all but the last 3 sections. The "
"\"Optional Features\" section lists flags that enable/disable features you "
"may be interested in. The \"Optional Packages\" section often lists "
"dependencies and the flags needed to locate them. The \"environment "
"variables\" section lists environment variables that the build system uses "
"to pass flags to the compiler and linker."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:233
msgid "Adding flags to configure"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:235
msgid ""
"For most of the flags you encounter, you will want a variant to optionally "
"enable/disable them. You can then optionally pass these flags to the "
"``configure`` call by overriding the ``configure_args`` function like so:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:238
msgid ""
"def configure_args(self):\n"
"    args = []\n"
"    ...\n"
"    if self.spec.satisfies(\"+mpi\"):\n"
"        args.append(\"--enable-mpi\")\n"
"    else:\n"
"        args.append(\"--disable-mpi\")\n"
"\n"
"    return args"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:251
msgid ""
"Alternatively, you can use the :ref:`enable_or_disable  "
"<autotools_enable_or_disable>` helper:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:253
msgid ""
"def configure_args(self):\n"
"    args = []\n"
"    ...\n"
"    args.extend(self.enable_or_disable(\"mpi\"))\n"
"    return args"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:262
msgid ""
"Note that we are explicitly disabling MPI support if it is not requested. "
"This is important, as many Autotools packages will enable options by default "
"if the dependencies are found, and disable them otherwise. We want Spack "
"installations to be as deterministic as possible. If two users install a "
"package with the same variants, the goal is that both installations work the "
"same way. See `here <https://www.linux.com/news/best-practices-autotools>`__ "
"and `here <https://wiki.gentoo.org/wiki/Project:Quality_Assurance/"
"Automagic_dependencies>`__ for a rationale as to why these so-called "
"\"automagic\" dependencies are a problem."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:270
msgid ""
"By default, Autotools installs packages to ``/usr``. We don't want this, so "
"Spack automatically adds ``--prefix=/path/to/installation/prefix`` to your "
"list of ``configure_args``. You don't need to add this yourself."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:277
msgid "Helper functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:279
msgid ""
"You may have noticed that most of the Autotools flags are of the form ``--"
"enable-foo``, ``--disable-bar``, ``--with-baz=<prefix>``, or ``--without-"
"baz``. Since these flags are so common, Spack provides a couple of helper "
"functions to make your life easier."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:285
msgid "``enable_or_disable``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:287
msgid ""
"Autotools flags for simple boolean variants can be automatically generated "
"by calling the ``enable_or_disable`` method. This is typically used to "
"enable or disable some feature within the package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:290
msgid ""
"variant(\n"
"    \"memchecker\",\n"
"    default=False,\n"
"    description=\"Memchecker support for debugging [degrades "
"performance]\",\n"
")\n"
"...\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def configure_args(self):\n"
"    args = []\n"
"    ...\n"
"    args.extend(self.enable_or_disable(\"memchecker\"))\n"
"\n"
"    return args"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:307
msgid ""
"In this example, specifying the variant ``+memchecker`` will generate the "
"following configuration options:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:309
msgid "--enable-memchecker"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:314
msgid "``with_or_without``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:316
msgid ""
"Autotools flags for more complex variants, including boolean variants and "
"multi-valued variants, can be automatically generated by calling the "
"``with_or_without`` method."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:318
msgid ""
"variant(\n"
"    \"schedulers\",\n"
"    values=disjoint_sets(\n"
"        (\"auto\",), (\"alps\", \"lsf\", \"tm\", \"slurm\", \"sge\", "
"\"loadleveler\")\n"
"    ).with_non_feature_values(\"auto\", \"none\"),\n"
"    description=\"List of schedulers for which support is enabled; \"\n"
"    \"'auto' lets openmpi determine\",\n"
")\n"
"if not spec.satisfies(\"schedulers=auto\"):\n"
"    config_args.extend(self.with_or_without(\"schedulers\"))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:331
msgid ""
"In this example, specifying the variant ``schedulers=slurm,sge`` will "
"generate the following configuration options:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:333
msgid "--with-slurm --with-sge"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:337
msgid ""
"``enable_or_disable`` is actually functionally equivalent to "
"``with_or_without``, and accepts the same arguments and variant types; but "
"idiomatic Autotools packages often follow these naming conventions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:340
msgid "``activation_value``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:342
msgid ""
"Autotools parameters that require an option can still be automatically "
"generated, using the ``activation_value`` argument to ``with_or_without`` "
"(or, rarely, ``enable_or_disable``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:344
msgid ""
"variant(\n"
"    \"fabrics\",\n"
"    values=disjoint_sets(\n"
"        (\"auto\",), (\"psm\", \"psm2\", \"verbs\", \"mxm\", \"ucx\", "
"\"libfabric\")\n"
"    ).with_non_feature_values(\"auto\", \"none\"),\n"
"    description=\"List of fabrics that are enabled; 'auto' lets openmpi "
"determine\",\n"
")\n"
"if not spec.satisfies(\"fabrics=auto\"):\n"
"    config_args.extend(self.with_or_without(\"fabrics\", "
"activation_value=\"prefix\"))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:356
msgid ""
"``activation_value`` accepts a callable that generates the configure "
"parameter value given the variant value; but the special value ``prefix`` "
"tells Spack to automatically use the dependency's installation prefix, which "
"is the most common use for such parameters. In this example, specifying the "
"variant ``fabrics=libfabric`` will generate the following configuration "
"options:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:359
msgid "--with-libfabric=</path/to/libfabric>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:364
msgid "The ``variant`` keyword"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:366
msgid ""
"When Spack variants and configure flags do not correspond one-to-one, the "
"``variant`` keyword can be passed to ``with_or_without`` and "
"``enable_or_disable``. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:369
msgid ""
"variant(\"debug_tools\", default=False)\n"
"config_args += self.enable_or_disable(\"debug-tools\", "
"variant=\"debug_tools\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:374
msgid "Or when one variant controls multiple flags:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:376
msgid ""
"variant(\"debug_tools\", default=False)\n"
"config_args += self.with_or_without(\"memchecker\", "
"variant=\"debug_tools\")\n"
"config_args += self.with_or_without(\"profiler\", variant=\"debug_tools\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:384
msgid "Conditional variants"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:386
msgid ""
"When a variant is conditional and its condition is not met on the concrete "
"spec, the ``with_or_without`` and ``enable_or_disable`` methods will simply "
"return an empty list."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:388
msgid "For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:390
msgid ""
"variant(\"profiler\", when=\"@2.0:\")\n"
"config_args += self.with_or_without(\"profiler\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:395
msgid ""
"will neither add ``--with-profiler`` nor ``--without-profiler`` when the "
"version is below ``2.0``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:398
msgid "Activation overrides"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:400
msgid ""
"Finally, the behavior of either ``with_or_without`` or ``enable_or_disable`` "
"can be overridden for specific variant values. This is most useful for multi-"
"value variants where some of the variant values require atypical behavior."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:403
msgid ""
"def with_or_without_verbs(self, activated):\n"
"    # Up through version 1.6, this option was named --with-openib.\n"
"    # In version 1.7, it was renamed to be --with-verbs.\n"
"    opt = \"verbs\" if self.spec.satisfies(\"@1.7:\") else \"openib\"\n"
"    if not activated:\n"
"        return f\"--without-{opt}\"\n"
"    return f\"--with-{opt}={self.spec['rdma-core'].prefix}\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:413
msgid ""
"Defining ``with_or_without_verbs`` overrides the behavior of a "
"``fabrics=verbs`` variant, changing the configure-time option to ``--with-"
"openib`` for older versions of the package and specifying an alternative "
"dependency name:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:415
msgid "--with-openib=</path/to/rdma-core>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:420
msgid "Configure script in a sub-directory"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:422
msgid ""
"Occasionally, developers will hide their source code and ``configure`` "
"script in a subdirectory like ``src``. If this happens, Spack won't be able "
"to automatically detect the build system properly when running ``spack "
"create``. You will have to manually change the package base class and tell "
"Spack where the ``configure`` script resides. You can do this like so:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:427
msgid "configure_directory = \"src\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:432
msgid "Building out of source"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:434
msgid ""
"Some packages like ``gcc`` recommend building their software in a different "
"directory than the source code to prevent build pollution. This can be done "
"using the ``build_directory`` variable:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:437
msgid "build_directory = \"spack-build\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:441
msgid ""
"By default, Spack will build the package in the same directory that contains "
"the ``configure`` script."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:444
msgid "Build and install targets"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:446
msgid "For most Autotools packages, the usual:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:448
msgid ""
"$ configure\n"
"$ make\n"
"$ make install"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/autotoolspackage.rst:454
msgid ""
